{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586030"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15050"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15050"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.46,0.08,0.15,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67570"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7738"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53022"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18899"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67570"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents two weeks after coronary angiography with livedo reticularis of the skin, blue discoloration of the toes, and abdominal pain. Blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEosinophil count: 1.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (0.0-0.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EComplement C3: 0.6 g/L (0.9-1.8)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate: 85 mm/hr (1-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polyarteritis nodosa","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura","Acute interstitial nephritis","Cholesterol embolism syndrome","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Echolesterol embolism syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as renal atheroembolic disease. The triad of peripheral signs (livedo reticularis, blue toes), eosinophilia, and hypocomplementaemia is characteristic. The timing after a vascular procedure is typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolyarteritis nodosa\u003C/strong\u003E causes systemic vasculitis but typically presents with more prominent constitutional symptoms and renal involvement\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E presents with thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute kidney injury and fever, without peripheral manifestations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically affects the upper respiratory tract and lungs with granulomatous inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECholesterol embolism syndrome typically occurs in patients with underlying atherosclerosis following vascular procedures or anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cholesterol emboli syndrome presents with peripheral signs (livedo reticularis, trash foot) and systemic features (eosinophilia, hypocomplementaemia)","Renal atheroembolic disease typically occurs after vascular procedures or anticoagulation in patients with atherosclerosis","The classic triad includes peripheral signs, eosinophilia, and hypocomplementaemia"],"references":["Shah N, Nagalli S. Cholesterol Emboli. 2024 Jan 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310551.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53022"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15050"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53022"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:16:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:18:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7738"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67570"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relati